<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#871f78">Originally posted by Faerianae on 08-18-2001 04:02 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">WOW!  I never imagined the person behind EQ Atlas was a medical student/doctor.  That is very impressive, as is the long list of fans supporting your site.  I was introduce to EQ by a friend who told me all about EQ Atlas, so I can't even imagine playing this game without a map.  As one person said, you don't take a real-life road trip without a map, so why would you venture into unknown zones on EQ just to get slain and never find your corpse again?  I looked over the Crushbone map again and again until I finally memorized the thing, and I still check back for details about what spawns where.  I never would have survived that place without you, and I see the spawning details as more of a life-saver than a spoiler.  IE:  it saved me from begging to get my corpse removed from the Throne Room because I wandered in unknowingly.

As for the book, you did the work, they should allow you to publish it.  My guess its the book would be cheaper than all the ink and paper I go through printing all the maps out, along with Ala's bestiaries.  I can't imagine wanting to bother with EQ without the maps.  They are not spoilers, they make EQ a lot of money money.

Keep on them and tell them to see how many of us pledge our 'undying' lives to your maps.  Maybe they will realize the importance of your site and the big customer base just waiting to hear your maps are out in print all in one BIG book.

Thanks so much for all your hard work, you have made this game much more enjoyable.  Decide what you must do for your own life, and I would be glad to help out in any way I can.

------------------
Faerianae, High Elf Pally and various other characters on EQ</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
